Consider the case illustrated in Figure 1(a), where a rotor is modeled as a cylinder with radius (
Rr
) and height (
H
), a stator with radius (
Rs
) and height (
H
), and the clearance with thickness (
ɛ
). The rotor is rotated by the stator and levitated by a vibrating plate. Hideyuki and Tomoo (2002) and Adi and Izhak (2003, 2006) have studied the near-field acoustic levitation and the relationship between the thickness of the squeeze film and levitation force is well revealed and discussed. The investigation of the levitation of the rotor is beyond the domain of this paper. Figure 1(b) shows the vibration mode of the stator surface. Because the surface vibrates periodically, the traveling wave rotates with an angular velocity (
ω
). As a consequence, the thickness of the squeeze film changes simultaneously resulting in pressure gradients and viscous forces, which can greatly rotate the rotor.
Figure 1.
Structure mode of the squeeze film: (a) Mode in X–Z plane; (b) Vibration mode of the stator surface in X–Y plane.
